# Why: Documenso's email-domain feature uses AWS SES purely as a
#      domain-verification middleman. The flow is:
#
#        1. Documenso generates an RSA keypair locally
#        2. Documenso registers the domain with SES (CreateEmailIdentityCommand)
#        3. User adds DKIM TXT record in their DNS zone
#        4. Documenso polls SES (GetEmailIdentityCommand) to ask "did the DNS
#           record propagate?"
#        5. SES does its own DNS lookup, returns SUCCESS/PENDING
#        6. Documenso updates EmailDomain.status accordingly
#
#      For our deployment, this is wasteful for two reasons:
#
#      a. We don't send mail through SES — Postmark handles all outbound.
#         The "registered identity" in SES is never used.
#      b. SES's DNS-lookup-as-a-service is just a middleman for what is
#         fundamentally a `dns.resolveTxt` call. We can do the same lookup
#         locally with zero AWS dependency.
#
#      This overlay replaces the SES integration with a local DNS TXT lookup.
#      Same domain-ownership security guarantee — only whoever controls the
#      DNS zone can add a TXT record at the DKIM selector path. The lookup
#      hits authoritative resolvers each call (slightly fresher than SES's
#      cached result, in fact).
#
#      Trigger: caught when user tried to add `circularpayments.com` via the
#      now-working email-domains UI (after overlay 008 unblocked the paywall)
#      and got "Missing AWS SES credentials" because we never set those env
#      vars. Choices were: provision AWS SES, patch SES out, or skip the
#      EmailDomain feature entirely. User chose patch-out.
#
# Files patched:
#
#   `packages/ee/server-only/lib/create-email-domain.ts` — removes the
#   `verifyDomainWithDKIM(...)` call (which sent CreateEmailIdentityCommand
#   to SES). The local RSA keypair generation, DB row creation, and DKIM
#   TXT record output are all kept as-is. Result: a new EmailDomain row is
#   created in PENDING status with the keypair stored encrypted.
#
#   `packages/ee/server-only/lib/verify-email-domain.ts` — replaces the SES
#   `GetEmailIdentityCommand` poll with a local `dns.resolveTxt` lookup
#   against the selector FQDN. Parses the v=DKIM1 record, extracts the p=
#   public-key value, byte-compares to the public key Documenso stored in
#   the DB. If match, sets status to ACTIVE; otherwise PENDING.
#
# Why-not-additive: both files live in `packages/ee/server-only/lib/` and
#      are upstream-owned. We can't add a new file in
#      `packages/bizrethink/server-only/` and have Documenso's existing
#      callers (verifyEmailDomainRoute and createEmailDomainRoute in
#      enterprise-router) magically use it without modification — the call
#      sites are hardcoded to import these specific module paths.
#
# Why-not-add-bizrethink-dep-to-ee: we could put the DNS helper in
#      `packages/bizrethink/server-only/` and add `@bizrethink/customizations`
#      as a dep of `@documenso/ee` (same pattern as overlay 007 did for
#      `@documenso/prisma`). But the DNS lookup is ~30 lines and lives
#      naturally inside the function that calls it. Inlining is simpler
#      than another package dependency, and it keeps the patch surface
#      contained within the upstream files we're already overriding.
#
# Upstream-merge-fragility: MEDIUM. Documenso may refactor the
#      email-domain creation/verification flow in future releases; if they
#      restructure these functions, the overlay needs re-applying. The
#      DNS-based replacement is itself stable (Node `dns` module is
#      ancient and won't change), so most merge work would be re-targeting
#      the patch at whatever new shape upstream lands on.
#
# Side effects:
#
#      - `getSesClient` and `verifyDomainWithDKIM` exports in
#        create-email-domain.ts become dead code. They still work if called
#        (would throw "Missing AWS SES credentials" at runtime), but no
#        in-repo caller invokes them after this overlay. Left in place
#        rather than deleted because deleting changes the export shape and
#        upstream-merge gets noisier.
#      - The AWS SES env vars (`NEXT_PRIVATE_SES_ACCESS_KEY_ID`, etc.) are
#        no longer read anywhere in the deployed code path. They can be
#        omitted from Coolify entirely.
#      - `@aws-sdk/client-sesv2` remains a dependency of `@documenso/ee` —
#        the file still imports it (only at the top of create-email-domain.ts
#        for `verifyDomainWithDKIM` even though we don't call it). Removing
#        the dep is a separate cleanup if we ever care; for now, ~5 MB extra
#        in the build is invisible.
#
# Status: APPLIED 2026-04-30 (after the user opted for Option B in the
#         email-domain blocker triage; chosen over Option A "provision AWS"
#         and Option C "skip EmailDomain entirely").

